narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: History of Canada and Quebec in a broad sense; how to find, analyze, and write about primary sources; how to write better history/humanities papers in general
I, of course, learned about Canada's formation and development into the modern day, but I also learned and reflected on what it means to be a historian.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: very relaxed in terms of weekly assignments and workload, interesting content and lots of interesting reading (the more you do the more you get out of it but little of it is really super required), very nice professor who is very engaging in seminar 
Weaknesses: more of a small lecture with occasional debates or presentations and less of a seminar with lots of discussion

excellent structure; readings not always covered but Gitlin is an absolute gem of a story-teller and historian; assignments were always relevant and Prof G assists you along the planning process for the final paper if you need it.

The strength of this course is Prof Gitlin. He is so committed to the material, but he is even more committed to his studentssomething I haven't experienced in many Yale courses. He organized outings to fellow students' hockey games and welcomed us all into his office to talk about Canadian history and life at Yale.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would definitely recommend it to someone who is interested the topic or even someone looking to take a history class, Prof. G is really wonderful and I think almost anyone can enjoy this class.
Please take this class! Prof Gitlin is a true gem, and the material is fascinating.
